-- slug: watermelon-calories-complete-guide
INSERT INTO public.blog_posts
  (slug, title, meta_description, featured_image_url, content, status, is_published, language, published_at, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES
  (
    'watermelon-calories-complete-guide',
    'Watermelon Calories: The Refreshing Truth About This Summer Favorite',
    'Discover the calories in watermelon - per cup, per slice, and per wedge. Plus hydration benefits, lycopene content, and weight loss tips.',
    'https://smsikaqybxtnzjvruhsa.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/blog-images/featured-1768517554325.webp',
    '<div><h2>Watermelon Calories: The Refreshing Truth About This Summer Favorite</h2><p>Few foods capture the feeling of summer like watermelon. Its sweet taste, bright color, and hydrating qualities make it a favorite around the world. If you’re watching your health, you’ll be glad to know watermelon is low in calories and packed with nutrition. Here’s what you need to know about watermelon calories.</p><hr><h2>Impressively Low Calorie Content</h2><p>A cup of diced watermelon has about 46 calories. This makes it one of the lowest-calorie fruits, so you can enjoy a generous serving without worrying about too many calories.</p><p>A classic watermelon wedge, like the kind you’d eat at a summer barbecue, has about 86 calories if it’s one inch thick. Even a big slice like this is still low in calories.</p><p>One hundred grams of watermelon provides only about 30 calories, among the lowest of any fruit per weight. This metric helps when comparing watermelon to other fruits or tracking intake precisely.</p><p>A whole mini watermelon, which weighs about 5 pounds and has about 3 pounds of edible fruit, contains about 410 calories. Most people wouldn’t eat a whole mini watermelon by themselves, but this shows you can eat a lot of watermelon for not many calories.</p><p>The calorie composMost of the calories in watermelon come from carbohydrates, with about 11 grams per cup. There’s very little protein or fat. Of those carbs, about 9 grams are natural sugars.<strong> So Low in Calories</strong></p><p>Watermelon gets its name for a reason—it’s about 92% water. This high water content means it has very few calories for its size.</p><p>If you compare watermelon to other fruits, a medium banana has about 105 calories, an apple has 95, and a cup of grapes has 62. Watermelon’s 46 calories per cup are lower than those of almost all other fruits.</p><p>Because watermelon is mostly water, you can eat a big, filling portion for fewer calories than you’d get from a smaller serving of heavier foods. This makes it a great choice if you want to feel satisfied without eating too many calories.</p><p>Watermelon does have sugar, but not as much as you might think. Even though it tastes very sweet, it actually has less sugar per serving than some fruits that don’t taste as sweet. Its fresh, clean flavor makes it seem sweeter than it really is.</p><hr><h2>Hydration Benefits</h2><p>Besides being low in calories, watermelon’s high water content helps keep you hydrated.</p><p>Eating watermelon contributes to daily fluid intake. While it shouldn''t replace drinking water, watermelon can supplement hydration, especially during hot weather or physical activity.</p><p>Watermelon also has electrolytes like potassium, which help your body stay hydrated. The mix of water and electrolytes makes it a good snack after exercise.</p><p>For those who struggle to drink enough water, eating watermelon is a tasty way to help meet their hydration needs. Plus, it gives you nutrients that plain water doesn’t have. Studies suggest that watermelon juice may reduce muscle soreness after exercise, attributed to an amino acid called citrulline, which watermelon contains in notable amounts.</p><hr><h2>Nutritional Content Beyond Calories</h2><p>Watermelon delivers more nutrition than you might expect from such a low-calorie fruit. antioxidant vitamin supports immune function, skin health, and iron absorption.</p><p>Vitamin A provides approximately 18% of daily needs through beta-carotene and other carotenoids. These compounds support eye health and immune function.</p><p>Lycopene is the antioxidant that gives watermelon its red color, and watermelon has a lot of it. In fact, it has more lycopene per serving than raw tomatoes, which are usually known for this nutrient. Research suggests lycopene may help with heart health and cancer prevention.</p><p>Citrulline is an amino acid in watermelon that turns into arginine in your body. This may help with blood flow and exercise performance. Watermelon is one of the best sources of citrulline you can eat.</p><p>A cup of watermelon gives you about 5% of your daily potassium needs, which helps regulate blood pressure and supports muscle function.</p><hr><h2>Different Ways to Enjoy Watermelon</h2><p>Watermelon''s versatility extends beyond simply eating fresh sliThe most common way to eat watermelon is to cut it into chunks or slices and serve it fresh. This keeps all the nutrition and the crisp texture people love. Watermelon juice or smoothies have a stronger flavor but lose the fiber. A cup of juice has about the same calories as fresh watermelon, but it’s easier to drink more, so watch your portions.</p><p>Frozen watermelon makes a sweet, refreshing snack. You can freeze chunks or make popsicles for a low-calorie alternative to ice cream.</p><p>Adding watermelon to salads brings sweetness and color to savory dishes. It goes especially well with feta cheese, mint, and balsamic reduction in summer salads.</p><p>Grilled watermelon is becoming more popular. A quick grill brings out its natural sweetness while keeping it refreshing.</p><p>Pickled watermPickling watermelon rind turns what’s usually thrown away into a tangy, crunchy topping. The rind has fewer calories than the red part and adds a unique texture to meals.<strong>d Blood Sugar</strong></p><p>Even though watermelon is sweet, its effect on blood sugar is more complex than it seems.</p><p>Watermelon has a high glycemic index, around 72 to 80, which might worry people watching their blood sugar. But the glycemic index doesn’t tell the whole story.</p><p>Glycemic load, which accounts for actual carbohydrate content per serving, tells a different story. Watermelon''s glycemic load is only about 5 per serving, considered low. The high water content means each serving contains relatively little total carbohydrate. For most people, even those with diabetes, eating a moderate amount of watermelon doesn’t cause big spikes in blood sugar. The important thing is to watch your portion size and see how your body reacts. Response.</p><p>If you have diabetes or are concerned about blood sugar, pay attention to how your body responds to watermelon. Many people can enjoy normal portions without problems, but everyone is different.</p><hr><h2>Watermelon for Weight Loss</h2><p>Watermelon offers several advantages foWatermelon has several benefits if you’re trying to lose weight.s you can eat satisfying portions for minimal calories. Feeling full matters for diet adherence, and watermelon provides volume without processed sugar. Watermelon’s natural sweetness can help satisfy your sweet tooth without processed sugar. If you want something sweet, watermelon delivers real flavor with far fewer calories than candy or desserts. ream, or baked goods.</p><p>High water content promotes hydration, which supports metabolism and can reduce huWatermelon doesn’t have a lot of fiber—about 0.6 grams per cup—but it still helps with digestion and can make you feel a bit fuller.th and adds slight satYou can eat watermelon as a snack between meals, as a dessert instead of something heavier, or before meals to help you feel full before eating higher-calorie foods.-calorie foods.</p><hr><h2>Selecting and StorPicking a good watermelon helps you get the most enjoyment from this healthy fruit.-calorie fruit.</h2><p>Look for a yellow spot on the bottom of the watermelon where it sat on the ground. This “field spot” means it’s ripe. If the spot is white or pale green, the melon was picked too soon. ipe watermelon sWeight is important—a ripe watermelon should feel heavy for its size, which means it’s full of water and juicy inside. termelon should produce a deep, hollow sound. Higher. You can also knock on the watermelon. A deep, hollow sound means it’s ripe, while a higher sound might mean it’s not ready yet.nd consume within five days for the best quality.</p><p>Pre-cut watermelon from stores offers convenience but typically costs more. Buying pre-cut watermelon is convenient, but it usually costs more and might not be as fres<strong>h as a whole melon you cut yourself.</strong></p><p>While watermelon is low-calorie and healthy, excessive consumption can cause digestive distress because of its high water and fiber content. Eating a lot may cause bloating or loose stools. The natural sugars aren’t a problem in normal amounts, but they add up if you eat several pounds. For most people, enjoying watermelon in reasonable&nbsp;<strong>amounts</strong>&nbsp;is just fine. This is actually lower than that of many fruits. Grapes contain about 15 grams per cup, mangoes about 23 grams, and bananas about 14 grams. Watermelon tastes sweet due to its clean flavor profile, not exceptionally high sugar content. The high water content dilutes sugar concentration per bite.</p><p><strong>Is watermelon good before bed?</strong></p><p>Watermelon can be eaten at any time, though its high water content might increase nighttime trips to the bathroom. The sugar is low and usually won’t affect your sleep. As a low-calorie evening snack, watermelon i<strong>s a great</strong>&nbsp;choice. Watermelon supports weight loss by providing. No food, including watermelon, actually burns fat. But watermelon can help with weight loss because it’s sweet, filling, and low in calories, so it can take the place of higher-calorie foods. Citrulline in watermelon may also help with exercise, which supports fitness goals. Watermelon is good for weight loss, but it’s not a miracle fat burner.le and nutritious. The white part between the green skin and red flesh of watermelon is edible and healthy. It has citrulline, fiber, and some vitamins. It tastes milder and is crunchier than the red part. Many cultures pickle or cook the rind instead of throwing it away. Eating the white part helps reduce waste and adds nutrition. Summer gathering? CalorieVision''s AI-powered photo analysis can instantly calculate the calories in your watermelon serving. Simply snap a photo and get accurate nutritional information in seconds.</p><p><strong>Try CalorieVision free</strong> and enjoy summer''s favorite fruit with complete confidence.</p><hr><h2>The Bottom Line</h2><p>Watermelon contains approximately 46 calories per cup, making it one of the lowest-calorie fruits you can eat. Its high water content—about 92%—keeps the calories so low while still providing hydration and nutrients, including C, the antioxidant lycopene, and the amino acid citrulline. These nutrients make watermelon genuinely beneficial rather than simply "allowed" because it''s low-calorie.</p><p>For weight management, summer refreshmWhether you want to manage your weight, cool off in the summer, or just enjoy a tasty fruit, watermelon is a great pick. Its low calories let you eat plenty without guilt, so you can satisfy your hunger and sweet tooth. And now you know exactly why it deserves its place in healthy eating.</p></div>',
    'published',
    true,
    'en',
